In order to study the motion of solutes inside orthorhombic lysozyme crystals, we take into account that proteins affect the dynamics of solute molecules. MD simulations provide information to the dynamic picture of the solute motion in the vicinity of protein molecules. The self-diffusion coefficient D, which has been widely used in both spectroscopic experiments and MD simulations, is a suitable parameter characterizing the dynamical behavior of solute in the water filled protein channels in protein crystals. The diffusion coefficient D, is related to the slope of the mean square displacement (MSD) of water molecules by the Einstein relation, which in d dimension is: 1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
